Message: Example: As a parent, I want to be able to save/adjust speaker configurations in different rooms of the house so I can be able control the noise levels for the kids.

Author: p0189
Message: Example: As a person who hosts social gatherings, I want to be able to control multiple different speakers and be able to adjust to a host's phone when needed.

Author: p0189
Message: Example: As a person who hosts LAN parties, I want to be able to allow multiple people to connect with their own personal device to the gaming setups and have a stable connection.

Author: p0189
Message: Example: As a person who works from home, I want to be able to disconnect audio from a headset and have it remain disconnected without disturbing others and be able to reconnect if need be.

Author: p0189
Message: Example: As a person living in a dorm, I want to be able to connect more devices to an already established audio setup (E.g., Dorm mates have speakers, a computer, and a TV, etc.) without having an awkward connection (Stuttering, etc.).

Author: p0189
Message: Example: As a person with a home theater, I want to be able to enjoy watching a movie with others and they have the ability to connect with their own personal headphones/earbuds.

Author: p0351
Message:
Spotify is one of the most popular music streaming services out there; it is also one of the most developer-friendly and provides excellent documentation for the steps needed to access data. This makes Spotify a good candidate for our first supported service.
 

 In order to resolve this issue, our program should:
 

 1. Accept login credentials for an active Spotify account
 2. Display playlists associated with that account.
 

 Question 1: What information do we want to display about the songs on our playlists? Song title, artist, album, ISRC code, song length, genre tags...?
 

 Note 1: I do not think we actually require a MusicMirror login for this step. It's certainly something we'll want early on, but it isn't necessarily required for the MVP of our first sprint. As long as our program is able to accept Spotify credentials and use them to view playlist info, those credentials don't _have_ to be saved. Yet.

Author: p0269
Message:
I can't be of help re: front end, but I can offer a snippet from a previous implementation of mine with spotipy
 

 ```
 import spotipy
 from spotipy.oauth2 import SpotifyOAuth
 import webbrowser
 

 CLIENT_ID = 'insert client id here'  
 CLIENT_SECRET = 'and secret here'
 REDIRECT_URI = 'http://localhost:8585/callback'
 SCOPE = 'playlist-read-private' # In case you want to retrieve self-made playlists too 
 

 sp = spotipy.Spotify(auth_manager=SpotifyOAuth(client_id=CLIENT_ID, client_secret=CLIENT_SECRET, redirect_uri=REDIRECT_URI, scope=SCOPE))
 webbrowser.open(sp.auth_manager.get_authorize_url())
 input("Input entire token from address bar after web browser completes loading.")
 

 playlists= sp.current_user_playlists()
 playlist_data = {playlist['name']: playlist['id'] for playlist in playlists['items']}
 print(f"{len(playlist_data)} playlists: {playlist_data}")
 

 ```
 

  Using the playlist ID, you could then iterate through and retrieve data from each song using the various spotipy endpoints

I think the code looks fine and am looking forward to viewing the aesthetic changes. Thank you for staying on top of things.
 

 We do need to address the merging conflicts. It looks like most of the conflicts regard binary files, the database, and code generated by Django to perform migrations. I don't think it's a big deal if those change as they are not pertinent for the implementation side of our project.
 

  This isn't particularly addressed toward this pull, but more of a general assertion for all of us. We should consider adding a .gitignore and removing binary files that are not needed for our implementation. We also should consider removing the database which is a potential security concern. Each developer can generate their own database for testing purposes on their own machine. We can discuss this during our next scrum to see how we'd like to handle this.

Author: p0102
Message:
I fixed a minor bug.
 

 Previously if a parent directory existed, but the child directory did not exist,
 the child directory would not have been created, and so the application
 would not be able to open that directory to write to it.
 

 I changed it so that even if the parent directory already exists, the child
 directory will still be created if it does not already exist.
 After that the appliation can use that directory without problems.

Message:
I changed run_daemon() to return int instead of bool.

  - it returns 1 if it failed because the daemon was already running
  - it returns 2 if it failed you don't have permissions to run the daemon

Author: p0078
Message:
Update line scanning for input files
 

 There was a sudden change to input file format that required a switch to regex for input file scanning.
 

 This new format meant there wouldn't be standardized positions of key words, so a lot of methods quickly became unviable and the only realistic option left was using regex. While this unfortunately results in adding the library 'stringr' to the dependency list, we're now able to use regex in all other parts of the R-code if needed.

Message:
Update document.R
 

 Managed to functionalize the file I/O, etc. to make it able to handle N data-sets, given that it doesn't cause overflow issues within R.
